<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title><%= pageTitle %> – Art of the Orient</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css?v=3">
</head>
<body>
  <%- include('partials/header', { headerClass, pageTitle }) %>
  <%- include('partials/page-wrap-start') %>
  <main class="main">
    <h2 class="gallery-title"><%= pageTitle %></h2>
    <section class="section-text section-text-full">
      <p>Pungsokdo — genre painting depicting the customs and everyday life of the Korean people — emerged as a major form of Korean pictorial art during the eighteenth century Joseon dynasty, representing a democratization of artistic subject matter that paralleled similar developments in the ukiyo-e tradition of Japan and the genre painting traditions of Europe, turning the painter's eye away from the elevated subjects of landscape, Buddhist imagery, and scholarly still life toward the vivid, immediate spectacle of ordinary Korean life in all its labor, leisure, humor, and social texture. The tradition's two greatest masters — Kim Hongdo, known by his artistic name Danwon, and Sin Yunbok, known as Hyewon — approached the genre from complementary angles that between them defined its full expressive range: Kim Hongdo's scenes of farmers, blacksmiths, wrestlers, tightrope walkers, and village schoolchildren rendered with warm, affectionate humor and a compositional economy that isolates his figures against plain grounds to focus all attention on the telling gesture or expression that captures the essence of a moment, and Sin Yunbok's more psychologically charged scenes of aristocratic leisure, romantic encounters, and the social world of the gisaeng — Korea's educated female entertainers — depicted with a sophistication of observation and an eye for the nuances of costume, social hierarchy, and human desire that gives his work a quality of social portraiture unmatched in the Korean tradition. Pungsokdo paintings were not merely decorative objects but documents of a society — records of how Koreans worked, played, worshipped, celebrated, and struggled — and their survival across the centuries gives them a historical dimension that deepens their artistic significance, preserving in brushwork and pigment a visual census of Joseon dynasty life that no written record could replicate with comparable immediacy and human warmth.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
  <%- include('partials/page-wrap-end') %>
  <script src="/js/nav.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
